    "analysis": "Previous step: the Executor loaded metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv and produced global aggregates (count, mean, P90, P95) grouped by cmdb_id + KPI/trace/log name. Observations from those aggregates: many components (29 distinct cmdb_id) and many metric/trace/log groups (several hundred). Log error_count aggregates show zeros for Tomcat and apache hosts. The error_logs grouped table was empty (no grouped error log records). No time-window filtering or anomaly detection has been done yet, so we don't know which components or KPIs breached their thresholds within the incident window (2021-03-23 14:30 to 15:00). Next we must perform anomaly detection on the metric series using global thresholds computed from the full series (P95 and P5). This will narrow candidate component-KPI faults before using traces and logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the full metric.csv series already loaded in kernel variables, compute global P95 and P5 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) (do NOT filter by time yet). Then filter metric.csv to the incident time window March 23, 2021 14:30 to 15:00 (Executor should handle timestamp<->datetime conversion). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name), detect anomaly points in the time window where value >= global P95 OR value <= global P5. Aggregate the anomalies per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and return up to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly count desc with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5. Also return a deduplicated list of cmdb_id that have anomaly_count>0. Keep output compact."
