{
    "analysis": "Anomaly detection (previous step) scanned metric groups using global P95/P5 and found multiple (cmdb_id, kpi_name) groups with anomalies inside the incident window 2021-03-23 14:30–15:00 CST. Many groups show anomaly_count == 31 (the full-window length), indicating the metric values during the window equal or exceed the global thresholds continuously. Top candidate cmdb_ids with anomalies include: ServiceTest2, Tomcat02, Tomcat04, IG01, IG02, ServiceTest1, MG01. No trace- or log-based localization has been done yet. We must now identify fault intervals (consecutive anomalous points) per anomalous group, filter noisy single-point spikes, and compute severity to prioritize the most likely root-cause faults.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) that had anomaly_count>0 in the previous anomalies_summary (use that anomalous groups set stored in kernel), extract its metric time series filtered to the incident window 2021-03-23 14:30 to 15:00 (Executor handles timestamp<->datetime). Using the global_p95 and global_p5 previously computed per group (from full series), detect consecutive anomalous runs where each minute's value meets anomaly condition (value >= global_p95 OR value <= global_p5). For each run (consecutive sequence of anomalous minutes) compute and return one row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, run_start_timestamp, run_end_timestamp, run_length_minutes, max_value_in_run, min_value_in_run, global_p95, global_p5, breach_type (\"high\" if value>=p95, \"low\" if value<=p5), severity_score (for high: (max_value - global_p95) / (abs(global_p95)+1e-9); for low: (global_p5 - min_value) / (abs(global_p5)+1e-9)). Filter out runs with run_length_minutes <= 1 (drop single-minute spikes). Return up to top 20 runs sorted by severity_score desc then run_length_minutes desc. Also return the deduplicated list of cmdb_id present in these returned runs.",
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous Executor steps performed preprocessing and metric-based anomaly/fault identification. Global thresholds (P95 and P5) were computed from full series. Within the incident window (2021-03-23 14:30–15:00 CST) the metric analysis produced 7 multi-minute fault runs (severity > 0.5) across six cmdb_id candidates: MG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Tomcat02, Tomcat04, and ServiceTest9. Many of these faults are binary-style network/process indicators flipping from 0→1 for almost the entire window (producing extremely large relative severity scores), while ServiceTest9 shows a short but notable low breach on app.cnt (2 minutes, severity ~0.76). At this stage we have multiple node-level faults; according to the diagnosis rules for a single failure we must (1) use traces to identify downstream faulty services/containers and (2) use logs to confirm the resource/reason. Traces will help determine which of these faulty nodes is most downstream in call flows or which exhibits latency/row_count anomalies that align temporally with metric faults. Therefore we should analyze trace telemetry for the candidate cmdb_ids inside the incident window using the precomputed global thresholds to find trace anomalies (duration, row_count, p95 metrics) and prioritize components that show trace-level degradation co-occurring with the metric faults.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel-stored trace.csv and the previously computed global P95/P5 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) (compute them from the full trace series if not yet available), scan only the candidate cmdb_id set: [\"MG02\",\"Mysql01\",\"Mysql02\",\"Tomcat02\",\"Tomcat04\",\"ServiceTest9\"]. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name):\n1) Filter trace points to the incident window 2021-03-23 14:30 to 15:00 CST (Executor handles timestamp<->datetime).\n2) Detect anomalies in the window where value >= global_p95 OR value <= global_p5.\n3) Aggregate anomalies per (cmdb_id, trace_name) and return up to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count desc then mean(value) desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, mean_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5.\nAlso return a deduplicated list of candidate cmdb_id that have trace anomalies (anomaly_count>0). Keep outputs compact and do NOT print full raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocess, metric anomaly detection, fault-run identification, trace analysis, and log scanning. Metric analysis produced multi-minute faults across MG02, Mysql01/02, Tomcat02, Tomcat04, and ServiceTest9; many of the highest-severity metric runs were binary 0→1 network/process flags on MG02 and Tomcat nodes. Trace anomalies concentrated on Tomcat02 and Tomcat04 (elevated trace.self.duration_p95 and high row_count flows involving MG02). Log anomalies show Tomcat02 and Tomcat04 had brief GC pause increases and request/row_count spikes during the window; MG02 had no log anomalies and no error_log entries were found for these hosts. Timing: metric runs included starts at 2021-03-23 14:30:00 CST, trace anomalies earliest ~14:31, and GC/log signals around 14:35–14:44. To localize the single root cause we must determine call-chain ordering between the faulty Tomcat nodes and MG02 and pick the most-downstream faulty component in the trace flow that also shows a significant metric breach and corroborating logs. The next step is a focused, compact trace-call-chain and earliest-anomaly timing extraction for the top candidates (Tomcat02, Tomcat04, MG02) so we can decide which faulty component is downstream and which component shows the first-occurring fault.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For candidate cmdb_id [\"Tomcat02\",\"Tomcat04\",\"MG02\"] do two compact extractions (Executor handles timestamp<->datetime conversions):\n1) From the kernel-stored trace anomaly table or by recomputing trace anomalies for these cmdb_id within 2021-03-23 14:30–15:00 CST using global P95/P5, return all anomalous trace groups whose trace_name contains 'from_' or 'to_' or 'to_MG'/'from_MG' (i.e., call-directional traces). For each row return: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, mean_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, global_p95. Limit to top 50 rows sorted by earliest_anomaly_timestamp asc then anomaly_count desc.\n2) From the kernel-stored metric fault runs (the previously computed multi-minute runs), return for these three cmdb_id a compact summary of the earliest run_start_timestamp and run details per component: cmdb_id, top_kpi_name (the KPI with the highest severity_score for that cmdb_id), severity_score, run_start_timestamp, run_length_minutes, breach_type. Limit to one row per cmdb_id (the top KPI by severity_score).\nKeep outputs compact. These two outputs will let us infer call directions, earliest fault times per component, and which component is the most-downstream faulty candidate in traces."
}

Review and final inference: After global-threshold metric analysis, fault-run detection, trace call-flow inspection, and log corroboration within 2021-03-23 14:30–15:00 (UTC+8), MG02 consistently appears as the downstream focal point with sustained TCP FIN/CLOSE_WAIT socket-state anomalies and multiple anomalous incoming row_count traces from Tomcat nodes. Tomcat nodes show upstream stress (GC and row_count spikes) but MG02 exhibits the strongest, earliest, and most downstream network-level deviation. Therefore the root cause is determined as a network connection handling problem at MG02 beginning at 2021-03-23 14:30:00 (UTC+8), best categorized as network packet loss.

